<i>Guorgonui</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["From the vocabulary word denoting the plant (Old English <i>fearn</i>). Modern use of this word as a given name dates from the 19th century, when it is also recorded occasionally as a boy's name in the United States. In some instances the given name may be a transferred use of the surname derived in the medieval period from the vocabulary word."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan ferch Gronwy was born about 1426, in Loughor, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom as the daughter of Gronwy ap Hywel. She had at least 3 sons with Dafydd Tew."},"et":{"ABT    1426–":"umbes 1426–Surnud","1426–Female":"1426–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1422–Male":"1422–Surnud","1448–Male":"1448–Surnud","1448":"1448","1426":"1426","about 1448":"umbes 1448","1422":"1422","ABT    1426":"umbes 1426","of Cwm, Flintshire, Wales":"Cwm, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of,Casllwchwr,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Loughor, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT    1426–":"noin 1426–Kuollut","1426–Female":"1426–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1422–Male":"1422–Kuollut","1448–Male":"1448–Kuollut","1448":"1448","1426":"1426","about 1448":"noin 1448","1422":"1422","ABT    1426":"noin 1426","of Cwm, Flintshire, Wales":"Cwm, Flintshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of,Casllwchwr,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Loughor, Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT    1426–":"environ 1426–Décédée","1426–Female":"1426–Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1422–Male":"1422–Décédé","1448–Male":"1448–Décédé","1448":"1448","1426":"1426","about 1448":"environ 1448","1422":"1422","ABT    1426":"environ 1426","of Cwm, Flintshire, Wales":"Cwm, Flintshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","of,Casllwchwr,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Loughor, Glamorgan, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Joan ferch Gronwy est née environ 1426, à Loughor, Glamorgan, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni, fille de Gronwy ap Hywel. Elle a eu au moins 3 fils avec Dafydd Tew."},"de":{"ABT    1426–":"um 1426–Verstorben","1426–Female":"1426–Versto